# PID Simulation — Agent SOP

Standard operating procedure for AI agents working on Mantik’s browser-based PID tuning trainer (`/pid-simulation`). Applies to **any mechanism** (elevator, arm, shooter, turret, etc.).

Read [`CLAUDE.md`](../../CLAUDE.md) for project handoff. This document captures **mistakes already made** and how to avoid repeating them.

---

## 1. What this product is (and is not)

| Is | Is not |
|----|--------|
| Training sim: edit boilerplate, tune gains, watch mechanism + graph | Real WPILib JVM, Gradle, YAMS runtime |
| Parser extracts constants from Java templates | Arbitrary Java compile/execute |
| Workflow mirror of Elastic / AdvantageScope / vendor tuners | Byte-identical copy of YAMS or desktop sim |

Link students to [mantik-pid-practice](https://github.com/itkan-robotics/mantik-pid-practice) for full local WPILib sim.

**Before implementing physics for a mechanism:** find the reference plant in mantik-pid-practice (or FRC lesson) and note **motor type**, **mass/inertia**, **gearing**, and **expected gain ranges** from the lesson video. Calibrate to those ranges — not to generic guesses.

---

## 2. Physics — read design doc first

**Before any physics work:** read [`vertical-elevator-sim-design.md`](../../src/lib/pid-sim/docs/vertical-elevator-sim-design.md).

### 2.1 Reference stack

Port from WPILib docs [controls_js_sim](https://github.com/wpilibsuite/wpilib-docs/tree/main/source/_extensions/controls_js_sim), not a hand-rolled Java RKDP clone:

- **Plant @ 5 ms:** `plant/verticalElevatorPlant.ts` (RK4, meters internal)
- **Controller @ 20 ms:** `sim/verticalElevatorSim.ts` (PID + FF + trapezoid profile)
- **Trapezoid profile:** WPILib incremental `calculate(dt, current, goal)` — not controls_js_sim absolute-time `init()` pattern (see design doc § Trapezoidal motion profiling)
- **Encoder delay:** `utils/delayLine.ts`
- **Loop docs:** [Physics Simulation with WPILib](https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/wpilib-tools/robot-simulation/physics-sim.html)

### 2.2 Vendor-specific motors

**Mistake:** Hardcoded `getNeo(1)` for all vendors.

**Rule:** Use `motorForVendor(vendor)` — REV → NEO, CTRE → Kraken X60. Vendor choice on landing affects **physics motor**, not Java boilerplate only.

### 2.3 Rotation-based PID (on-controller units)

**Mistake:** PID in meters (V/m) while SparkMax/Talon FX encoders report motor rotations.

**Rule:**

- Templates, SpringTune, and PID math use **motor rotations** (setpoint, kP in V/rot, kV in V/(rot/s)).
- Mechanism view and TraceView display **meters** (convert via `encoderUnits.ts`).
- WPILib docs JS sim uses meters in the controller — Mantik deliberately uses rotations to match vendor tuners.

### 2.4 kG / feedforward

| Mechanism | kG behavior |
|-----------|-------------|
| Elevator | Constant voltage `kG` |
| Arm / turret | `kG · cos(position)` |
| Flywheel | No kG |

**Rule:** Plant `getHoldVoltage()` must match steady-state physics. Tests: kG = hold → stable; kG = 0 → falls; kG too high → creeps up.

### 2.5 What not to do

- Do not hardcode `getNeo(1)` for CTRE paths
- Do not use V/m kP or golden CSV JVM trace validation
- Do not put hidden friction in the plant while exposing `kS` in FF
- Do not add `pidOutputScale` hacks

### 2.6 Unit tests required

Add `*.test.ts` under `src/lib/pid-sim/physics/`:

- REV vs CTRE hold voltage differs
- kG hold / drift / creep
- kP = 0 vs kP > 0 motion toward setpoint
- Descent vs ascent distance (gravity assist)

Run: `npm run test:physics`

